Australian University to develop new drug promising to treat blood vessel blockages caused by new crown - Xinhua - RT News
Sydney, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Researchers at Monash University in Australia are developing a new drug that can help prevent heart disease and stroke, and hope it can be used to treat blood vessel blockages caused by the new crown virus.
Researchers found that an enzyme in the platelets accelerates platelet clotting before a heart attack or stroke.
As a result, they developed a drug that temporarily inhibits platelet clotting, thereby preventing blood vessels from clogging and preventing heart disease and stroke.
Researchers say the drug will only suppress the clotting effect of platelets when signs of heart disease or stroke appear.
With studies showing that similar blood vessel blockages are one of the leading causes of death in new coronary artery disease patients, researchers hope the drug could be used in the future in the treatment of such serious patients.
Currently, the drug has shown good results in animal model experiments, and researchers are preparing for the next phase of human clinical trials.
Research has been published in the American Journal of Science and Translational Medicine.
