Is it reasonable to sue the school after the 3-year-old children's college playground was smashed?
2020-07-26 05: 01: 11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
Playground smashed, children awarded compensation before suing school
Correspondent Zhao Yifan
The 3-year-old was playing in a college playground when he was accidentally hit in the head by a softball team's Chen while pitching.
As a result of the settlement of the case, the court ordered the school to pay compensation to the school where the incident took place, and to pay medical expenses and compensation for moral damages totalling 20,000 yuan.
Recently, after hearing the case, the Beijing Haidian District People's Court held that the school had installed a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident, that it had done its proper safety and security obligations, and that Chen had made compensation, and accordingly rejected the plaintiff's claim.
Mr. Wen claims that during the summer of 2019, he took Xiao Wen to play in the school playground while the softball team was training in the playground.
In order to avoid the risks associated with this, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents operate in a safe area designated by the softball team.
However, the player was then thrown off the pitch, causing the ball to fly over the guard net and hit the back of the head.
Mr Wen immediately took Xiao Wen to hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with a head trauma.
Mr Wen argued that the facilities on the school pitch did not comply with relevant safety regulations and did not effectively manage the team and associated facilities.
The failure of the school resulted in the incident, which caused considerable physical and psychological suffering to the boy and his family, for which the school should be held legally liable.
In response, the school argued that the school had installed protective netting in the playground, and posted management regulations, training notices, told the playground to keep a safe distance from the training site and warned of its own safety, and that the plaintiffs could not prove that the school "did not meet its safety and security obligations," so they
The court heard that the site of the incident was a site open to the public by the university in question and that, although the school had a duty of safety and security with respect to the management of the playground, this duty of safety and security should only be met
At the time of the incident, the school installed a protective net in the playground, and has done its proper safety and security obligations, and Chen has also compensated Xiaowen for medical expenses, transportation costs and other losses of more than 2,000 yuan according to a previous compensation agreement.
Afterwards, the parents again sought compensation from the school, which was unfounded, and the court ruled against the plaintiffs.
Neither party appealed the judgement, which is now in force.
According to article 37 of our tort liability law, schools, as managers of public places, have safety and security obligations; in the case of damage caused by the actions of a third person, the third person is liable for infringement, and the manager of a public place who does not meet the safety and security obligations should
According to the judge, since, as the manager of a public place, it is most likely to know the actual situation in the place as a whole, to anticipate the danger and damage that may occur, to take the necessary measures to prevent loss or to mitigate the extent of the damage, and to avoid and mitigate the least cost of the damage, the law
In the present case, the safety and security obligations of the school should be commensurate with its social activities, in particular the obligation to take basic security measures and to inform of hidden dangers, in respect of the non-specific access to the playground, which is open to the public free of charge.
In judicial practice, it is also inappropriate to impose excessive safety and security obligations on managers of public places.
If the school has put in place a protective net and has a duty to inform, the school may be found not to be at fault and not liable.
In addition, the liability of the superintendent of a public place, such as a school, is supplemental to the liability of a third person for damages, even if the superintendent of a public place, such as a school, fails to comply with the obligation of safety and security. Under the
In such cases, the victim should therefore not have to extend the scope of the claim after having received compensation from the direct infringer.
