As a country with a population of 1.4 billion and a size similar to that of Europe or the United States, the new coronary epidemic is under effective control at this stage, without any further widespread transmission, and the epidemic in China is largely under control.
China has invested heavily in domestic research and public health construction for more than a decade, the article said, making China's preparation for the new crown far more adequate than that for severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) that year.
The authors say that when SARS erupted in 2002, China was initially ill-prepared, especially for pathogens.
When the new coronavirus was discovered in December 2019, Chinese scientists were soon able to identify the virus species and share genome sequencing data with the international community on January 11, 2020.
By the end of January, doctors from mainland China and Hong Kong had clarified the clinical characteristics of the virus, warning the world of the threat of the new coronavirus through research papers published in The Lancet.
China has also been at the forefront of vaccine research, which was conducted very quickly and rigorously under a state of emergency declared by the state, and the results of early trials of a new coronary vaccine developed in China were published in The Lancet in May and July, respectively.
The experience of China has shown the importance of investing in national health and research systems to effectively improve laboratory capacity.
This is the basis for a rapid and effective national response to health emergencies and global health security.
Other countries, especially low- and middle-income countries, have much to learn.
Moreover, China's experience has shown that strong research is needed to make sound decisions based on strong, high-level and decisive scientific evidence, so that the new crown epidemic can be effectively controlled.
The article stresses that governments and their leaders must respect science, understand its value and act on it in the best way for society.
In the early stages of the outbreak, the National Health and Construction Commission of China sent three teams of infectious disease experts to Wuhan to investigate the risks and spread of the new crown virus, and their recommendations informed the decision to "seal the city" of Wuhan on January 23.
The article concludes by emphasizing that responding to global health emergencies requires countries to strengthen global cooperation and joint responses.
